      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Benchmark problems with known analytical solutions (beam bending, Hertzian contact) reproduced within 1% error using the same element formulations employed in the pedicle screw model.",
      "rationale": "Three benchmark cases — Euler-Bernoulli cantilever beam, thick-walled cylinder under internal pressure, and Hertzian contact between a sphere and flat — were executed using SOLID186 and CONTA174/TARGE170 elements. All results within 0.8% of analytical solutions, confirming numerical correctness of the element library for this application."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence study demonstrates QoI change <2% between the production mesh and a uniformly refined mesh with half the global element size.",
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh refinement study (0.8 mm, 0.4 mm, 0.2 mm global element size) was conducted. Richardson extrapolation yielded a GCI of 1.3% for construct stiffness and 1.7% for yield force. The production 0.4 mm mesh is confirmed to be in the asymptotic convergence regime."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Newton-Raphson residual norms converge to below 1e-4 at each load step; energy criterion also satisfied.",
      "rationale": "All 200 substeps converged with force residual norm below 5e-5 and displacement residual norm below 2e-5. No unconverged substeps or bisection events were recorded. Energy criterion satisfied at every increment, confirming numerical solution integrity."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Independent peer review of model setup, boundary conditions, material assignments, and contact definitions completed by a second analyst not involved in model construction.",
      "rationale": "An independent senior analyst reviewed the APDL command stream, material card assignments, contact pair definitions, and boundary condition application against the analysis plan. Three minor discrepancies were identified and corrected prior to final simulation runs. No material errors remained at the time of validation result generation."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Linear elastic material model with isotropic hardening plasticity (bilinear) for Ti-6Al-4V; frictional contact at screw-rod and screw-vertebral body block interfaces. Model form consistent with published literature for this construct type.",
      "rationale": "The bilinear isotropic hardening model for Ti-6Al-4V is well-established for quasi-static structural analysis of spinal implants. Frictional contact at the polyaxial head-rod interface captures the dominant nonlinearity observed experimentally. Geometric nonlinearity (large deflection) is enabled, consistent with the 40 mm displacement range in the test protocol."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties sourced from ASTM F136-13 coupon testing of the same material lot used to manufacture the test constructs. Geometric dimensions taken from engineering drawings with tolerances applied as nominal values.",
      "rationale": "Elastic modulus (114 GPa), yield strength (880 MPa), and tangent modulus (1.2 GPa) were derived from tensile coupon tests on Ti-6Al-4V bar stock from the same heat as the screw blanks. Coefficient of friction (0.25) is consistent with published values for Ti-Ti contact under dry conditions and was confirmed by a dedicated pin-on-disk tribology measurement."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "N=11 constructs assembled from production-representative components; dimensional inspection confirms all critical features within drawing tolerances.",
      "rationale": "Eleven constructs were assembled using production-intent non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screws and 5.5 mm cobalt-chrome rods. Dimensional inspection of each screw confirmed thread pitch, outer diameter, and core diameter within ±0.05 mm of nominal. UHMWPE vertebral body blocks machined to ASTM F1717 geometry from a single billet."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions span the range of clinically relevant loading rates and environmental conditions. At minimum, two distinct test conditions should be evaluated.",
      "rationale": "Testing was conducted under a single set of conditions (ambient temperature, dry, 5 mm/min crosshead speed) as specified by ASTM F1717. No variation in loading rate, temperature, or fluid environment was explored. This factor is below the required level; the limitation is acknowledged and the overall credibility determination accounts for this gap via the remaining margin in other factors."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation boundary conditions and material inputs are demonstrably equivalent to the experimental setup; any deviations are quantified and shown to have negligible effect on QoIs.",
      "rationale": "Boundary conditions in the FEA (fixed base block, displacement-controlled upper block, free rotation about the bending axis) replicate the ASTM F1717 fixture kinematics. The only deviation is the idealized rigid fixture representation; a sensitivity study showed less than 0.5% change in stiffness QoI when fixture compliance was included using measured values."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Normalized error metric E/uval < 1.96 for all three QoIs; percentage difference < 10% for each QoI.",
      "rationale": "All three QoIs (construct stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm) satisfy both acceptance criteria. E/uval values of 1.41, 1.28, and 1.55 are all below the 1.96 threshold. Percentage differences of 6.3%, 5.8%, and 8.7% are all below the 10% bound. Validation uncertainty uval was computed from experimental repeatability (N=11) and model input uncertainty via Monte Carlo propagation."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) are directly linked to the clinical risk hypothesis and the regulatory submission claim.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness governs load sharing with the vertebral column; yield force is the primary fatigue-life surrogate; force at 40 mm captures post-yield behavior relevant to worst-case implant loading. All three QoIs are cited in the 510(k) predicate comparison and are standard ASTM F1717 output metrics."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation scenario (ASTM F1717 static compression-bending, non-cannulated 7.5 mm screw, UHMWPE blocks) is sufficiently representative of the COU to support extrapolation of credibility conclusions.",
      "rationale": "The validation scenario directly replicates the regulatory test standard and the device geometry of record. The only extrapolation required for the COU is from bench-test loading to in vivo loading, which is addressed by the conservative nature of the ASTM F1717 protocol. The validation activities are therefore judged highly relevant to the COU."
    }
